<font color="#FF0000">LANGUAGE AND PERCEPTIONS</font><br>
<tt>Thu Aug 14 23:07:52 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook,<br><br>
If you truly honored the enemy soldiers, as you say you do, then honor them with your language as well.  &quot;Gook&quot; is not an honorable way of referring to people.<br><br>
I understand your needs to describe your battle situations, but remember that this site was named &quot;Vietnam, Stories Since the War.&quot;  I too am writing a book on my USAF experiences, including Vietnam, but I will not post long passages recounting my experiences in-country unless it is pertainent to the discussions at hand, and then I will keep it shorter.  <br><br>
I have been moved by many of your writings, but again wish you to realize that some of what you say, and how you are saying it, tend to reinforce the stereotypes people have of Vietnam Veterans.  <br><br>
I understand also that you do not have a problem with the language you use, and that is the preblem. This is the last comment I will have on this subject, as I do have better things to do.
<p><code>-- searat@sorcom.com  (John C. Ratliff) </code><p>


